nd spatial organisation of urban houses during the period, ranging across the social spectrum from the large courtyard mansions occupied by members of the mercantile and civic elite, to the homes of the urban "middling sort" and the small two- and three-roomed cottages of the city's weavers andartisans. The so-called "age of transition" witnessed profound social and economic changes and religious and political upheavals, which Norwich, as a major provincial capital, experienced with particular force and intensity; domestic life was also transformed. The author examines the twin themes of continuity and change in the material world and the role of the domestic sphere in the expression and negotiation of shifting power relationships, economic structures and social identities in the medieval and early modern city. CHRIS KING is Assistant Professor of Archaeology at the University of Nottingham.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecture and society-History-England-Norwich. 0aArchitecture, DomesticzEnglandzNorwichxHistory. 0aArchitecture, Domestic-History-England-Norwich. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aBritish Local History. 4aMedieval History. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aArchitectural History.  aArtisans.  aAuthority.  aCarrow Road.  aCraftsmen.  aEast Anglia.  aGreat Rebuilding.  aMerchants.  aNorfolk.  aNorwich.  aPower.  aReformation.  aSocial Identity.  aSotherton.  aUrban Culture.  aUrban Landscape.  aVernacular Architecture.  avernacular.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787449329?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787449329423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787449329/